Python Project - (Prosper Loan Analysis)¶

by (Ndivhuwo Netshiendeulu)¶

Introduction¶

The dataset contains details of the Prosper Loan customers or borrowers. This dataset has 113937 rows and 81 columns. Proper loan is a lending company that offers loans to various borrowers and investment options for investors. Borrowers apply money for personal loans and credit cards. The dataset shows details about the loans from the listing data to origination date and also the closed date. This dataset will be cleaned, analysed and visualized.

# Inset a new column called IncomeRangeClass based on the StatedMonthlyIncome and using conditions on the IncomeRange and the StatedMonthlyIncome
#First set the conditions and the values for if the condition is met

conditions = [
    (df['StatedMonthlyIncome'] <=24999),
    (df['StatedMonthlyIncome'] > 24999) & (df['StatedMonthlyIncome'] <= 49999),
    (df['StatedMonthlyIncome'] > 49999) & (df['StatedMonthlyIncome'] <= 74999),
    (df['StatedMonthlyIncome'] > 74999) & (df['StatedMonthlyIncome'] <= 99999),
    (df['StatedMonthlyIncome'] > 99999)
    ]
# create a list of the values we want to assign for each condition
values = ['Poor', 'LowerMiddleClass', 'MiddleClass', 'UpperMiddleClass','Rich']

# create a new column and use np.select to assign values to it using our lists as arguments
df['IncomeRangeClass'] = np.select(conditions, values)

What are the distribution(s) of the variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Where any transformations done on the variables?¶

The histograms show that the dataset is positively skewed, meaning that the outliers in the distribution are towards the right.
No I did not transform the data.

Where there any unusual distributions in the variables that were investigated? Was there any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why?¶

I did not want to delete the null values and lose valuable information, so i performed the following operations:

  • The null values in employment status were replaced with a new category called 'Unknown'.
  • The null values in credit rating were replaced with a new category called 'Unknown'.
  • The null values in Delinquencies last 7 year were replaced with random values, which were estimated through interpolation (linear forward interpolation).

There were some blanks on the previous income range that was originaly in the data, but i noticed that i can use the stated monthly income to get an estimate of the icome range for each borrower, by creating a column called income range class:

  • The income range class, these ranges were created based on the stated monthly income and the income range column that was there before, the classes for the income range were based on the income groups from https://money.usnews.com/money/personal-finance/family-finance/articles/where-do-i-fall-in-the-american-economic-class-system

The graph also shows that some of the loans borrowed from 2011 to 2014 are past due on their payments, most of these loans were below 25000. There are a few loans amounts that were above 25000 during the period between 2013 and 2014. For the period between 2014 and 2015, we see only current loans.

The relationships observed in the key features¶

  • The dominant credit rating for most borrowers is 'C', this was for the poor income range class and 'employed' and 'full-time' employment status.
  • Most borrowers are in the poor income range and they are either employed or full-time employed. While the highest number of borrowers in the poor income range fall into the 'employed' employment status.
  • The maximum monthly loan payment for most borrowers in the poor income range class is around 380, however there are some outliers that pay above this maximum value, the outliers pay monthly amounts as high as 1400.
  • The maximum monthly loan payment for most borrowers in the lower middle income range class is around 610.
  • The middle class income range ays around 190 per month
  • The rich income range class pays around 410 per month
  • Most loans have an origination date of less than 10 months.
  • Delinquencies over the last 7 years were high, when the monthly loan payment was 1000.
  • Loan amounts less than 25000 have high borrower interest rates.
  • And investors mostly invest in loan amounts that are less than 25000.

Other interesting relationships between the other features that were not part of the key features¶

A large number of open revolving accounts had less than 50 total inquiries at the time the credit profile was pulled

Conclusions¶

The dataset shows that from 2005 to 2015 most loans are either completed or current, most loans that are completed and current are for loan amounts that are less than 25000. Most loans have an origination date of less than 10 momths. Borrowers mostly apply for loan amounts that are less than 25000. The appearance of loans that are past due on payment is noticed between 2011 to 2015. The borowwer are mostly in the poor income range class and lower middle income range class. Some borrowers took loans that were above 25000 between 2013 and 2014. Most borrowers pay less than 1000 in monthly payments, but a few are able to pay more than 1000 per month. Monthly loan payments less than 1000 caused a large number of delinquencies in the last 7 years. Although most investors preffer to invest in small amounts of loans (less than 25000), there are a few who invest in loans that are more than 25000. There is a large amount of borrowers that are in the poor income range class and they also indentify as employed and full-time, and for these borrowers the largest credit rating is C, and the second largest credit rating is B. The borrowers in the lower middle class have a credit rating of 'D', they also classify into the 'employed' employment status. Borrowers with loan amounts less than 25000, pay high interest rates than borrowers who borrow more than 25000 amounts of loans.

The data exploration process included:

  1. Changing the datatype for the dates to datetime:
  • All columns that contain dates were changed from object type to datetime
  1. Dropping columns that were not key features:
  • Other columns that were identified as not being part of the key features were dropped
  1. Sample selection:
  • This involved choosing a random sample of the original dataset. The number of random samples is 2353, it was estimated for 95% confidence interval, and 2% margin of error, this sample number was calculated using the sample calculator from https://www.checkmarket.com/sample-size-calculator/
  1. Replacing null values:
  • The null values in employment status were replaced with a new category called 'Unknown'.
  • The null values in credit rating were replaced with a new category called 'Unknown'.
  • The null values in delinquencies last 7 year were replaced with random values, which were estimated through interpolation (linear forward interpolation).
  • The null values in total inquiries were replaced with random values, which were estimated through interpolation (linear forward interpolation).
  1. Creating new columns by:
  • Creating a new column from the overall credit rating, this column was a combination of the credit grade (for listings per 2009) and prospoer rating(Alpha) for listings post 2009.
  • There were some blanks on the previous income range that was originaly in the data, but i noticed that i can use the stated monthly income to get an estimate of the icome range for each borrower, by creating a column called income range class:
  • The income range class, these ranges were created based on the stated monthly income and the income range column that was there before, the classes for the income range were based on the income groups from https://money.usnews.com/money/personal-finance/family-finance/articles/where-do-i-fall-in-the-american-economic-class-system
